Returning to the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have tabled a bill to establish the organization of unions as a civil right.
"Just as unions die, the middle-class jobs are dying, too," said Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
Therefore, I proudly present the Employee Empowerment Act together with the civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal options in discrimination on grounds of organizing unions as other forms of discrimination - and thus stops anti-unionized forces.
Supplementing the National Labour Law Act to create a possibility for discrimination-suspended workers to organize a trade union representation, to sue for justice in a civil court - and to receive damages or fines - is a meaningful and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to connect back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks faced by unions in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand and comply with labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to pass a constitution to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojo would be replaced by democracy.
Aware of the fact that the workers and their unions were taking a role in the creation of a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly acknowledged that "the rights of workers to union and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing the fact that the workers would have to organize, and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly stated: "The right to establish associations to secure and improve the working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that restrict or aim to reduce this right are null and void; measures aimed at this are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Human Rights Commission, of which the Universal Declaration of Human Rights was drafted, as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the other writers placed a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form or join unions to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to shape civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to establish a trade union - and to the fact that this union could then participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies - must be protected.
Since these rights came under fire in America, it is actually very wise to revisit the American ideal, according to which the working people must have the right to unite and make themselves heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
The story is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the workers' movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions of people, Labor has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
The story remembers, and we should do that too.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and deliver on the promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily halts law that all Louisiana abortion clinics could force closure
A federal judge on Sunday provisionally halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana that lawyers say it would presumably have led to the closure of all five abortion clinics in the state.
This measure, which was brought to law by Bobby Jindal, governor of Louisiana, in June and on the 1st Sept. is to come into effect, would force doctors who perform abortions to acquire a patient admission right at a hospital within a 30-mile radius around their practice.
However, the judge's decision means doctors can continue to legally perform abortions for the time being while they are applying for such a right.
"The plaintiffs may continue to work in accordance with the law while seeking to obtain these rights," Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling.
Within a month, a hearing will be scheduled for the judge to bring about a more permanent decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying doctors thus gain more time to gain hospital admission rights.
"Today's decision means that the women in Louisiana are evading a sneaky law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and chairwoman of the Center for Reproduction Rights, which had sued on behalf of three of the state's five clinics to halt the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the verdict also extended to the doctors from the two clinics who had not joined the lawsuit and also applied for admission rights.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws, with courts recently declaring such measures in Alabama and Mississippi non-constitutional.
Key points of a law in Texas that would have forced most of the clinics remaining in the state to close were stopped by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, consistently say that admission rights require unnecessary restrictions from doctors.
Abortion opponents counter that the measures serve to protect women's health, although some also welcomed the effects of closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has patient admissions, the Center for Reproduction Rights said.
If all the other doctors in the state are forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would no longer perform the operation out of fear for his safety, the group said.
In their argument against the ruling, representatives of the state of Louisiana said they would not punish doctors for performing abortions, while whose requests for patient admission rights would still be pending.
