4 Tips for Better Underwater Photos and Videos
If you would like to take photos or videos underwater, there is a selection of devices.
The cheapest option is a waterproof point-and-shoot, like the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action cam like the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both available for about $300.
I took these photos at a family party with several cameras, all available at a price of under $350.
Regardless of the equipment, there are a few rules for the best results.
Check your equipment twice.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure that the battery compartment and other compartments are tightly sealed.
Also, set your camera to the photos or videos you want to capture.
Some cameras and camcorders have scene and shooting modes that optimize exposure time for the dusky underwater conditions.
And before you jump in, check to what depth your equipment is functional.
Some cameras are only approved for up to 5 feet, others up to 50 or 60 feet.
Search our shopping guide and reviews for digital cameras for traditional and waterproof models.
Take multiple shots - because many won't work.
Point-and-shoot cameras have an LCD that allows you to compose images, action cams usually do not.
Even if you have an LCD, it is difficult to look at this underwater, and the correct image setting is a matter of luck.
So you take a lot of shots.
If your camera has a row mode that takes a series of shots with slightly changed exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The light gets dramatically worse the further you move away from the surface.
So if possible, stay close to the surface when you take pictures in a pool, lake or sea.
This will also allow you to bring more color to your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Walk close to the objects.
This is also good advice on land, but it is all the more important underwater because of the low light conditions.
It is especially important if you work with an action cam: These devices often have a fixed wide-angle lens, which means that you have to close to your objects if you want them to fill the entire picture frame.
