We showed a mighty tribe in our puzzle task of the summer series "Mein Stück vom Rhöner Glück" last Friday.
Several of these tree giants still exist in the district, the pictured specimen is the "Geissruheriche" above Unterweißenbrunn.
A bumpy footpath leads up to the approximately 600-year-old oak tree.
It passes by paddocks, basalt stone heaps and basalt stone seas.
A little below the quarry from the Bauersberg, a kilometer north of the road to Weisbach, there it stands.
Vital looks the natural monument, it protrudes beyond the other trees of the surrounding area and is reminiscent of an American sequoia tree with a circumference of over eight meters.
A small Buddha on a tree stump indicates that it is a spiritual or mystical place.
But despite intensive research, there were only references to the origin of the name.
Dr. Wolfgang Schneider consulted the Bischofsheimer Archive and interviewed older people from Unterweißenbrunn to learn what kind of knowledge it has with the cheess.
The result of his investigations remained the rather sober explanation for the name.
Until about 80 years ago, the goat herders drove their animals from Unterweißenbrunn onto the arduously cleared meadows and freed from stones.
At the foot of the tree, the animal guardians exhausted from the ascent are said to have rested.
In the meantime, the area has regained its importance, because in the meadows, goat herds actually graze again.
The area has also been declared the core zone of the biosphere reserve, Schneider has further found out.
When entering the stone accumulations, however, one should exercise caution, because the basalt warmed up by the sun is also a popular place for cross otters.
A hiking trail leads from Unterweißenbrunn to the tree, but it is somewhat hidden.
Further paths are signposted, climb up the direction Hochrhön and invite you to an extended hike.
