Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded Russian media reports on Sunday that the Ukrainian government cease fighting against the separatists in the east of the country and immediately begins negotiations on the "statehood" of the breakaway region.
His spokesman, Dimitry Peskov, later clarified that Putin did not mean that the territory of eastern Ukraine under the control of the separatists would become part of Russia, but that his status to Ukraine had to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
However, Putin's call for the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents fits the strategy he has apparently pursued since the riots began five months ago: help for the separatists in taking areas and pressure on the Ukrainian government to allow the newly proclaimed Novorossiya region de facto independence for an alliance with Russia instead of the West.
In an interview with state television channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to recapture the separatist-held areas in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were taken in March and April, after Moscow's Crimea peninsula on 18. March had annexed.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently referred to the territory taken as "Novorossiya" or "New Russia," a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary heyday of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the wake of Ukrainian politicians' campaigns, for the elections on 26. Oct. and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in the areas held by separatists hope for early peace talks hope "in their illusions," Itar-Tass reported.
"We must immediately start detailed discussions, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of southeastern Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said that Putin's reference to statehood must be seen in context with the greater autonomy, which has been under discussion for months by the Kiev leadership to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern territories, Peskov said.
This is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin spokesman's clarification on the correction of the "misinterpretation" of Putin's remarks underscored Russia's claim to leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the East as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, on which the majority of the 2 million inhabitants are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty in annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million residents are not Russians and polls from before the conflict yielded a broad majority for remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy, addressed by Russian diplomats on international forums, would give the regional governments in Ukraine authority to negotiate their own trade agreements and foreign relations, thus de facto giving the Kremlin control over an area that connects Russian territory with Crimea.
The peninsula in the Black Sea, which was annexed five months ago, is the home port for the majority of the Russian navy, as well as an important trading port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that make important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko struck in his speech at the inauguration on 7. June in front of the Ukrainian legislation should consider - after new elections - additions to the constitution, with which the respective territories are given greater control over their finances and the status of the languages.
But his notion of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to those of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whose arming and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin's last call to Kiev to negotiate with separatist leaders on an equal footing followed after another advance by the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks invaded eastern Ukraine over the previously peaceful region along the Sea of Azov.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoazovsk in the hands, which, according to fears of Ukrainian security officials, is the first step of a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region as far as Crimea.
